              <tr><td><strong>De-indexing (spam)</strong></td><td>Manual or algorithmic</td><td>Sometimes</td><td>Full site clean-up + reconsideration</td><td>6-12+ months</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real Google penalty examples</h2>

        <h3>Example 1 — Link scheme manual action</h3>
        <p>A roofing company discovers their former SEO agency built 2,000 links from private blog networks and paid directories over three years. Google issues a manual action for unnatural inbound links. The fix: remove the links where possible by contacting webmasters, disavow the remainder through Search Console, and submit a reconsideration request with a full explanation of what was done and a commitment not to repeat it. Full recovery takes 4 months.</p>

        <h3>Example 2 — Algorithmic Helpful Content hit</h3>
        <p>A recipe blog publishes 500 AI-generated articles with minimal editing between June and September 2023. After the September 2023 Helpful Content Update, traffic drops 78%. There is no manual action notification — it's algorithmic. Recovery requires rewriting or removing the low-quality content and demonstrating genuine expertise across multiple update cycles. Some pages recover; others remain suppressed for over a year.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Manual action vs algorithmic adjustment — key differences</h2>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Manual Action</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Triggered by human review of a specific violation</li>
              <li>You receive a notification in Search Console</li>
              <li>The specific issue is named and described</li>
              <li>Recovery: fix the specific issue + reconsideration request</li>
              <li>Google reviews and responds within weeks of submission</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Algorithmic Adjustment</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Triggered automatically by an algorithm update</li>
              <li>No notification — only a traffic drop</li>
              <li>Requires diagnosis to identify the cause</li>
              <li>Recovery: fix underlying issues and wait for next update cycle</li>
              <li>Timeline depends on when Google re-runs the algorithm</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 practices to avoid Google penalties</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Never buy links.</strong> No matter how discreetly packaged as "sponsored content" or "editorial placements," paid links for SEO purposes violate Google's guidelines and create manual action risk.</li>
          <li><strong>Audit your backlink profile quarterly.</strong> Use Google Search Console, Ahrefs, or Semrush to monitor for spammy links. New toxic links can appear without your knowledge — especially if you've had previous SEO work done.</li>
          <li><strong>Vet every SEO vendor before hiring.</strong> Ask specifically: "How do you build links?" and "What content methods do you use?" Any answer involving buying links, link exchanges, or article spinning is disqualifying.</li>
          <li><strong>Publish original, helpful content.</strong> Content written to rank rather than to genuinely help readers is the primary target of algorithmic adjustments. The question is always: "Does this actually answer the query better than what's already ranking?"</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor for manual actions monthly.</strong> Check Search Console's Manual Actions section regularly. Catching a manual action early and submitting a prompt reconsideration request reduces the traffic impact window.</li>
          <li><strong>Set up a disavow file proactively.</strong> If you're in a competitive niche, maintain a disavow file in Search Console and update it as you discover spammy links. Don't wait for a penalty to start this practice.</li>
          <li><strong>Follow Google's Webmaster Guidelines precisely.</strong> Not approximately. The guidelines specifically address cloaking, hidden text, link schemes, and thin content. Each of these is a manual action trigger when detected.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — assuming algorithmic drops are penalties</div>
          <p>Many site owners panic and submit reconsideration requests when they see traffic drops, even when there is no manual action. Reconsideration requests are only for manual actions. For algorithmic drops, the fix is improving content or links — not submitting a request. Filing a reconsideration request when there's no manual action wastes Google's review queue and delays response to legitimate manual actions.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common Google penalty mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Confusing algorithmic drops with penalties.</strong> Most significant traffic drops after an update are algorithmic adjustments, not manual actions. Treat them differently.</li>
          <li><strong>Submitting reconsideration requests before fixing the issue.</strong> Google rejects incomplete requests. Fix every instance of the violation, document the work, then submit.</li>
          <li><strong>Disavowing legitimate links.</strong> Over-eager disavowal of good links during a link cleanup can remove beneficial authority. Only disavow links that are genuinely spammy, irrelevant, or paid.</li>
          <li><strong>Assuming the penalty will pass on its own.</strong> Algorithmic adjustments don't self-resolve — they require fixing the underlying issue. Waiting without acting extends the traffic loss.</li>
          <li><strong>Not documenting recovery steps.</strong> Reconsideration requests require evidence of the fix. Sites that document what they removed, when they removed it, and why it violated guidelines get faster responses than those with vague descriptions.</li>
        </ul>

